In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims November 2010 as National Family Caregivers Month. He acknowledges the important role that family members, friends, and neighbors play in providing essential care and assistance to their loved ones, including children, elders, and individuals with disabilities. The President recognizes that caregivers often face physical, psychological, and financial hardships while caring for their loved ones, and he emphasizes the need to support and assist them. He highlights the National Family Caregiver Support Program, which provides resources and services such as information, counseling, training, support groups, and respite care for caregivers across the country. The President also mentions the efforts made by his Administration's Middle Class Task Force to support family caregivers, including the implementation of the Affordable Care Act and the Community Living Assistance Services and Supports (CLASS) Program, which aims to provide insurance coverage and compensation for family caregivers. Additionally, he encourages businesses and companies to offer flexible work arrangements and paid leave to employees with caregiving responsibilities. The President concludes by honoring the millions of Americans who selflessly provide care for their family members and encourages all Americans to pay tribute to these caregivers.